PIETERMARITZBURG – A man has appeared in the Pietermaritzburg Magistrate’s Court in connection with a hydroponic dagga laboratory in the city, the Directorate for Priority Crime Investigation (Hawks) in KwaZulu-Natal said on Saturday. READ: Dagga worth R70k seized in KZN, four men arrested Hawks members from the Pietermaritzburg organised crime unit arrested Johan Bezuidenhout, 46, on Wednesday for operating a hydroponic dagga laboratory in the Oak Park area in Pietermaritzburg, Captain Simphiwe Mhlongo said. 
	(Pic: SAPS.) “Members received information about a man who was dealing in dagga in the area. A search warrant was obtained and they proceeded to the said place. Upon their arrival, a search was conducted and dagga plants with the street value of approximately R258,000 were found in the house. Bezuidenhout was subsequently arrested and the equipment used for cultivating dagga was also seized.”
	
	Bezuidenhout appeared briefly in the Pietermaritzburg Magistrate’s Court on Thursday, and was granted R1000 bail. The case was postponed to November 29, Mhlongo said. African News Agency